01:58:56.930 --> 01:59:00.230
But mercy is above thissceptred sway.

2287
01:59:00.230 --> 01:59:03.800
It is enthroned in thehearts of kings.

2288
01:59:03.800 --> 01:59:07.200
It is an attribute to Godhimself.

2289
01:59:07.200 --> 01:59:11.030
And earthly power doththen show likest God's

2290
01:59:11.030 --> 01:59:14.030
when mercy seasonsjustice.

2291
01:59:14.030 --> 01:59:18.000
Therefore, Jew, thoughjustice be thy plea,

2292
01:59:18.000 --> 01:59:21.630
consider this that, in thecourse of justice,

2293
01:59:21.630 --> 01:59:25.470
none of us should seesalvation.

2294
01:59:25.470 --> 01:59:27.200
We do pray for mercy,

2295
01:59:27.200 --> 01:59:30.200
and that same prayer dothteach us all

2296
01:59:30.200 --> 01:59:33.600
to render the deeds ofmercy.

2297
01:59:33.600 --> 01:59:37.670
I have spoke thus much tomitigate the justice ofthy plea.

2298
01:59:37.670 --> 01:59:40.100
Which, if thou follow, thisstrict court of Venice

2299
01:59:40.100 --> 01:59:43.200
must needs give sentence'gainst the merchant there.

2300
01:59:45.430 --> 01:59:47.900
My deeds upon my head.

2301
01:59:47.900 --> 01:59:53.830
I crave the law, the penaltyand forfeit of my bond.

2302
01:59:57.670 --> 02:00:00.430
Is he not able todischarge the money?

2303
02:00:00.430 --> 02:00:02.170
Yes, here.

2304
02:00:02.170 --> 02:00:03.900
I tender it for him in thecourt.

2305
02:00:03.900 --> 02:00:05.700
Yea, twice the sum.

2306
02:00:05.700 --> 02:00:09.570
If that will not suffice,I will be bound to pay itten times o'er

2307
02:00:09.570 --> 02:00:11.800
on forfeit of my hands, myhead, my heart.

2308
02:00:11.800 --> 02:00:13.530
If this will not suffice,

2309
02:00:13.530 --> 02:00:17.100
it must appear that malicebears down truth.

2310
02:00:17.100 --> 02:00:19.130
And I beseech you,

2311
02:00:19.130 --> 02:00:21.630
wrest once the law to yourauthority

2312
02:00:21.630 --> 02:00:24.270
to do a great right, do alittle wrong,

2313
02:00:24.270 --> 02:00:26.570
and curb this cruel devilof his will.

2314
02:00:26.570 --> 02:00:28.130
It must not be.

2315
02:00:28.130 --> 02:00:31.570
There is no power inVenice can alter a decreeestablished.

2316
02:00:31.570 --> 02:00:34.000
'Twill be recorded for aprecedent,

2317
02:00:34.000 --> 02:00:36.800
and many an error by thesame example will rushinto the state.

2318
02:00:36.800 --> 02:00:38.000
It cannot be.

2319
02:00:38.000 --> 02:00:39.300
A Daniel come to judgment.

2320
02:00:39.300 --> 02:00:41.870
Yea, a Daniel.

2321
02:00:41.870 --> 02:00:46.270
Oh, wise young judge, howI do honor thee.

2322
02:00:46.270 --> 02:00:48.200
I pray you, let me lookupon the bond.

2323
02:00:48.200 --> 02:00:50.600
Here 'tis, most reverenddoctor.

2324
02:00:50.600 --> 02:00:52.330
Here it is.

2325
02:00:52.330 --> 02:00:53.630
Shylock,

2326
02:00:53.630 --> 02:00:57.800
there's thrice thy moneyoffered thee.

2327
02:00:57.800 --> 02:01:02.670
An oath, an oath, I havean oath in heaven.

2328
02:01:02.670 --> 02:01:05.700
Shall I lay perjury uponmy soul?

2329
02:01:05.700 --> 02:01:07.930
No, not for Venice.

2330
02:01:10.400 --> 02:01:12.130
Why, this bond is forfeit,

2331
02:01:12.130 --> 02:01:15.470
and lawfully by this,

2332
02:01:15.470 --> 02:01:17.670
the Jew may claim a poundof flesh

2333
02:01:17.670 --> 02:01:21.870
to be by him cut off nearestthe merchant's heart.

2334
02:01:21.870 --> 02:01:23.100
Be merciful.

2335
02:01:23.100 --> 02:01:24.330
Take thrice thy money.

2336
02:01:24.330 --> 02:01:26.000
Bid me tear the bond.

2337
02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:28.400
When it is paid accordingto the tenor.

2338
02:01:28.400 --> 02:01:31.930
It doth appear you are aworthy judge.

2339
02:01:31.930 --> 02:01:33.570
You know the law.

2340
02:01:33.570 --> 02:01:36.670
Your exposition hath beenmost sound.

2341
02:01:36.670 --> 02:01:38.870
I charge you, by the law,

2342
02:01:38.870 --> 02:01:41.200
whereof you are awell-deserving pillar,

2343
02:01:41.200 --> 02:01:43.330
proceed to judgment.

2344
02:01:43.330 --> 02:01:47.400
By my soul, I swear thereis no power in the tongueof man to alter me.

2345
02:01:47.400 --> 02:01:49.000
I stay here on my bond.

2346
02:01:49.000 --> 02:01:51.970
Most heartily, I dobeseech the court to givethe judgment.

2347
02:01:51.970 --> 02:01:55.270
Why then, thus it is.

2348
02:01:55.270 --> 02:01:57.700
You must prepare yourbosom for his knife.

2349
02:01:57.700 --> 02:01:59.730
Oh, noble judge.

2350
02:01:59.730 --> 02:02:01.700
Oh, excellent young man.

2351
02:02:01.700 --> 02:02:04.870
For the intent and purposeof the law hath fullrelation to the penalty

2352
02:02:04.870 --> 02:02:06.470
which here appeareth dueupon the bond.

2353
02:02:06.470 --> 02:02:07.600
'Tis very true.

2354
02:02:07.600 --> 02:02:11.000
Oh, wise and uprightjudge.

2355
02:02:11.000 --> 02:02:12.900
How much more elder artthou than thy looks.

2356
02:02:12.900 --> 02:02:14.970
Therefore, lay bare yourbosom.

2357
02:02:14.970 --> 02:02:17.070
Ay, his breast.

2358
02:02:17.070 --> 02:02:18.970
So says the bond.

2359
02:02:18.970 --> 02:02:20.330
Doth it not, noble judge?

2360
02:02:20.330 --> 02:02:21.900
Nearest his heart.

2361
02:02:21.900 --> 02:02:23.000
Those are the very words.

2362
02:02:23.000 --> 02:02:24.170
It is so.

2363
02:02:24.170 --> 02:02:26.200
Are there balance here toweigh the flesh?

2364
02:02:26.200 --> 02:02:27.600
I have them ready.

2365
02:02:27.600 --> 02:02:30.170
Have by some surgeon,Shylock, on your charge,

2366
02:02:30.170 --> 02:02:33.830
to stop his wounds, lesthe do bleed to death?

2367
02:02:33.830 --> 02:02:35.500
Is it so nominated in thebond?

2368
02:02:35.500 --> 02:02:38.000
It is not so expressed,but what of that?

2369
02:02:38.000 --> 02:02:40.400
'Twere good you do so muchfor charity.

2370
02:02:40.400 --> 02:02:43.100
I cannot find it.

2371
02:02:43.100 --> 02:02:45.430
'Tis not in the bond.

2372
02:02:45.430 --> 02:02:48.970
You, merchant, have youanything to say?

2373
02:02:48.970 --> 02:02:50.470
But little.

2374
02:02:50.470 --> 02:02:53.570
I am armed and wellprepared.

2375
02:02:53.570 --> 02:02:57.030
Give me your hand,Bassanio.

2376
02:02:58.600 --> 02:03:01.500
Fare you well.

2377
02:03:03.030 --> 02:03:07.300
Grieve not that I amfall'n to this for you,

2378
02:03:07.300 --> 02:03:12.430
for herein, fortune showsherself more kind than isher custom.

2379
02:03:12.430 --> 02:03:16.070
It is still her use to letthe wretched man outlivehis wealth

2380
02:03:16.070 --> 02:03:17.970
to view with hollow eyeand wrinkled brow

2381
02:03:17.970 --> 02:03:20.700
an age of poverty fromwhich lingering penance

2382
02:03:20.700 --> 02:03:22.470
of such misery doth shecut me off.

2383
02:03:22.470 --> 02:03:26.570
Commend me to yourhonorable wife.

2384
02:03:26.570 --> 02:03:29.700
Tell her the process ofAntonio's end.

2385
02:03:29.700 --> 02:03:33.070
Say how I loved you.

2386
02:03:33.070 --> 02:03:36.070
Speak me fair in death.

2387
02:03:36.070 --> 02:03:37.900
And when the tale is told,

2388
02:03:37.900 --> 02:03:41.470
bid her be judge whetherBassanio had not once a love.

2389
02:03:41.470 --> 02:03:43.770
Repent but you that youshall lose your friend,

2390
02:03:43.770 --> 02:03:46.630
and he repents not that hepays your debt.

2391
02:03:46.630 --> 02:03:48.800
For if the Jew do cut butdeep enough,

2392
02:03:48.800 --> 02:03:51.500
I'll pay it instantly withall my heart.

2393
02:03:51.500 --> 02:03:56.370
Antonio, I am married to awife which is as dear tome as life itself,

2394
02:03:56.370 --> 02:03:58.730
but life itself, my wife,and all the world

2395
02:03:58.730 --> 02:04:01.470
are not with me esteemedabove thy life.

2396
02:04:01.470 --> 02:04:03.470
I would lose all, ay,sacrifice them all

2397
02:04:03.470 --> 02:04:06.270
here to this devil, todeliver you.

2398
02:04:06.270 --> 02:04:08.300
Your wife would give youlittle thanks for that

2399
02:04:08.300 --> 02:04:10.200
if she were by to hear youmake the offer.

2400
02:04:10.200 --> 02:04:12.730
I have a wife who Iprotest I love.

2401
02:04:12.730 --> 02:04:14.070
I would she were inheaven,

2402
02:04:14.070 --> 02:04:18.330
so she could entreat somepower to change thiscurrish Jew.

2403
02:04:18.330 --> 02:04:20.170
'Tis well you offer itbehind her back.

2404
02:04:20.170 --> 02:04:23.070
The wish would make elsean unquiet house.

2405
02:04:23.070 --> 02:04:26.130
These be the Christianhusbands?

2406
02:04:27.770 --> 02:04:31.900
I have a daughter.

2407
02:04:31.900 --> 02:04:34.430
Would any of the stock ofBarabbas

2408
02:04:34.430 --> 02:04:37.930
had been her husbandrather than a Christian.

2409
02:04:41.570 --> 02:04:44.600
We trifle time.

2410
02:04:44.600 --> 02:04:47.570
I pray thee, pursuesentence.

2411
02:04:52.330 --> 02:04:56.700
A pound of that samemerchant's flesh is thine.

2412
02:04:56.700 --> 02:05:01.170
The court awards it, andthe law doth give it.

2413
02:05:01.170 --> 02:05:04.070
Most rightful judge.

2414
02:05:04.070 --> 02:05:06.230
And you must cut thisflesh from off his breast.

2415
02:05:06.230 --> 02:05:10.170
The law allows it, and thecourt awards it.

2416
02:05:10.170 --> 02:05:12.470
Most learned judge.

2417
02:05:15.000 --> 02:05:17.300
A sentence!

2418
02:05:28.500 --> 02:05:29.800
Come...

2419
02:05:32.370 --> 02:05:34.400
prepare.

2420
02:05:50.870 --> 02:05:54.030
Tarry a little; there issomething else.

2421
02:05:54.030 --> 02:05:58.800
This bond doth give theehere no jot of blood.

2422
02:05:59.070 --> 02:06:02.970
The words expressly are "apound of flesh."

2423
02:06:02.970 --> 02:06:05.170
Take then thy bond.

2424
02:06:05.170 --> 02:06:08.130
Take thou thy pound offlesh.

2425
02:06:08.130 --> 02:06:11.570
But in the cutting of itif thou dost shed one dropof Christian blood,

2426
02:06:11.570 --> 02:06:15.400
thy lands and goods are,by the laws of Venice,

2427
02:06:15.400 --> 02:06:17.370
confiscate unto the stateof Venice.

2428
02:06:17.370 --> 02:06:18.600
Oh, upright judge!

2429
02:06:18.600 --> 02:06:19.900
Mark, Jew.

2430
02:06:19.900 --> 02:06:20.970
Oh, learned judge.

2431
02:06:22.700 --> 02:06:27.070
Is that the law?

2432
02:06:27.070 --> 02:06:28.330
Thyself shall see the act.

2433
02:06:28.330 --> 02:06:30.700
For, as thou urgestjustice,

2434
02:06:30.700 --> 02:06:33.630
be assured thou shalthave justice more thanthou desirest.

2435
02:06:33.630 --> 02:06:34.930
Oh, learned judge.

2436
02:06:34.930 --> 02:06:36.730
Mark, Jew, a learnedjudge.

2437
02:06:39.900 --> 02:06:45.030
I take this offer then.

2438
02:06:45.030 --> 02:06:47.870
Pay the bond thrice andlet the Christian go.

2439
02:06:47.870 --> 02:06:49.130
Here is the money.

2440
02:06:49.130 --> 02:06:51.100
Soft, the Jew shall haveall justice.

2441
02:06:51.100 --> 02:06:52.330
Soft, no haste.

2442
02:06:52.330 --> 02:06:54.070
He shall have nothing butthe penalty.

2443
02:06:54.070 --> 02:06:56.130
Oh, Jew, an upright judge.

2444
02:06:56.130 --> 02:06:57.570
A learned judge.

2445
02:06:57.570 --> 02:07:01.600
Therefore prepare thee tocut off the flesh.

2446
02:07:01.600 --> 02:07:02.830
Shed thou no blood,

2447
02:07:02.830 --> 02:07:07.600
nor cut thou less nor morebut just a pound of flesh.

2448
02:07:07.600 --> 02:07:10.370
If thou tak'st more orless than just a pound,

2449
02:07:10.370 --> 02:07:14.170
be it so much as makes it lightor heavy in the substance

2450
02:07:14.170 --> 02:07:17.600
or the division of thetwentieth part of onepoor scruple,

2451
02:07:17.600 --> 02:07:21.230
nay, if the scale do turn butin the estimation of a hair,

2452
02:07:21.230 --> 02:07:25.470
thou diest, and all thygoods are confiscate.

2453
02:07:25.470 --> 02:07:26.770
A second Daniel.

2454
02:07:26.770 --> 02:07:27.930
A Daniel, Jew.

2455
02:07:27.930 --> 02:07:32.170
Now, infidel, I have youon the hip.

2456
02:07:32.170 --> 02:07:34.100
Why doth the Jew pause?

2457
02:07:34.100 --> 02:07:35.500
Take thy forfeiture.

2458
02:07:54.000 --> 02:07:55.830
Give me my principal andlet me go.

2459
02:07:55.830 --> 02:07:57.070
I have it ready for thee.

2460
02:07:57.070 --> 02:07:58.230
Here it is.

2461
02:07:58.230 --> 02:07:59.770
He hath refused it in theopen court.

2462
02:07:59.770 --> 02:08:01.530
He shall have merelyjustice and his bond.

2463
02:08:01.530 --> 02:08:04.430
A Daniel still say I, asecond Daniel.

2464
02:08:04.430 --> 02:08:06.500
I thank thee, Jew, forteaching me that word.

2465
02:08:06.500 --> 02:08:09.330
Shall I not have barely myprincipal?

2466
02:08:09.330 --> 02:08:11.170
Thou shalt have nothingbut the forfeiture

2467
02:08:11.170 --> 02:08:15.070
to be so taken at thyperil, Jew.

2468
02:08:18.770 --> 02:08:23.030
Why then, the devil givehim good of it.

2469
02:08:26.370 --> 02:08:29.200
I'll stay no longerquestion.

2470
02:08:29.200 --> 02:08:33.430
Tarry, Jew, the law hathyet another hold on you.

2471
02:08:35.900 --> 02:08:38.470
It is enacted in the lawsof Venice

2472
02:08:38.470 --> 02:08:41.700
if it be proved against analien

2473
02:08:41.700 --> 02:08:44.070
that by direct or indirectattempts

2474
02:08:44.070 --> 02:08:46.270
he seek the life of anycitizen,

2475
02:08:46.270 --> 02:08:49.230
the party 'gainst thewhich he doth contrive

2476
02:08:49.230 --> 02:08:51.400
shall seize one half hisgoods.

2477
02:08:51.400 --> 02:08:55.670
The other half comes to theprivy coffer of the state.

2478
02:08:55.670 --> 02:09:00.500
And the offender's lifelies in the mercy of theDuke only

2479
02:09:00.500 --> 02:09:02.830
'gainst all other voice.

2480
02:09:05.070 --> 02:09:06.970
In which predicament I saythou stand'st,

2481
02:09:06.970 --> 02:09:10.870
for it appears by manifestproceedings

2482
02:09:10.870 --> 02:09:13.730
that indirectly, anddirectly too,

2483
02:09:13.730 --> 02:09:16.670
thou hast contrivedagainst the very life ofthe defendant,

2484
02:09:16.670 --> 02:09:21.670
and thou hast incurred thedanger formerly by merehearsed.

2485
02:09:21.670 --> 02:09:24.970
Down therefore, and begmercy of the Duke.

2486
02:09:31.330 --> 02:09:34.730
Beg that thou mayst haveleave to hang thyself.

2487
02:09:34.730 --> 02:09:37.230
And yet, thy wealth beingforfeit to the state,

2488
02:09:37.230 --> 02:09:40.330
thou hast not left thevalue of a cord.

2489
02:09:40.330 --> 02:09:45.400
Therefore, thou must behanged at the state's charge.

2490
02:09:45.400 --> 02:09:47.500
That thou shalt see thedifference of our spirit,

2491
02:09:47.500 --> 02:09:50.030
I pardon thee thy lifebefore thou ask it.

2492
02:09:50.030 --> 02:09:54.800
For half thy wealth, it isAntonio's.

2493
02:09:54.800 --> 02:09:57.070
The other half comes tothe general state

2494
02:09:57.070 --> 02:10:01.370
which humbleness may driveinto a fine.

2495
02:10:01.370 --> 02:10:03.630
Ay, for the state, not forAntonio.

2496
02:10:03.630 --> 02:10:07.030
Nay, take my life and all.

2497
02:10:07.030 --> 02:10:09.670
Pardon not that.

2498
02:10:09.670 --> 02:10:13.300
You take my house when youdo take the prop

2499
02:10:13.300 --> 02:10:15.300
that doth sustain myhouse.

2500
02:10:15.300 --> 02:10:19.200
You take my life when youdo take the means wherebyI live.

2501
02:10:19.200 --> 02:10:21.330
What mercy can you renderhim, Antonio?

2502
02:10:21.330 --> 02:10:22.630
A halter gratis.

2503
02:10:22.630 --> 02:10:24.030
Nothing else, for God'ssake.

2504
02:10:24.030 --> 02:10:30.300
So please, my lord, theDuke, and all the court,

2505
02:10:30.300 --> 02:10:32.730
to quit the fine for onehalf of his goods,

2506
02:10:32.730 --> 02:10:34.070
I am content.

2507
02:10:34.070 --> 02:10:37.530
So he will let me have theother half in use,

2508
02:10:37.530 --> 02:10:41.300
to render it upon hisdeath unto the gentleman

2509
02:10:41.300 --> 02:10:42.830
that lately stole hisdaughter.

2510
02:10:42.830 --> 02:10:45.500
Two things provided more:

2511
02:10:45.500 --> 02:10:49.930
that for this favor, hepresently become a Christian.

2512
02:10:51.230 --> 02:10:53.330
The other, that he dorecord a gift

2513
02:10:53.330 --> 02:10:56.070
here in the court of allhe dies possessed

2514
02:10:56.070 --> 02:10:59.000
unto his son, Lorenzo, andhis daughter.

2515
02:10:59.000 --> 02:11:02.800
He shall do this, or elseI do recant

2516
02:11:02.800 --> 02:11:06.300
the pardon I latepronounced here.

2517
02:11:06.300 --> 02:11:07.470
Art thou contented, Jew?

2518
02:11:07.470 --> 02:11:08.600
What dost thou say?

2519
02:11:17.430 --> 02:11:19.800
I am content.

2520
02:11:22.930 --> 02:11:25.530
Clerk, draw a deed ofgift.

2521
02:11:56.730 --> 02:12:02.770
I pray you, give me leaveto go from hence.

2522
02:12:07.970 --> 02:12:09.730
I am not well.

2523
02:12:12.200 --> 02:12:15.400
Send the deed after me,and I will sign it.

2524
02:12:16.800 --> 02:12:19.530
Get thee gone, but do it.

2525
02:12:31.330 --> 02:12:35.030
In christening, thou shalthave two godfathers.

2526
02:12:35.030 --> 02:12:37.000
Had I been judge, thoushouldst have had ten more

2527
02:12:37.000 --> 02:12:40.500
to bring thee to thegallows, not to the font.

2528
02:12:45.030 --> 02:12:50.300
Sir, I entreat you homewith me to dinner.

2529
02:12:50.300 --> 02:12:52.730
I humbly do desire yourgrace of pardon.

2530
02:12:52.730 --> 02:12:55.430
I must away this nighttoward Padua,

2531
02:12:55.430 --> 02:12:57.530
and it is meet I presentlyset forth.

2532
02:12:57.530 --> 02:13:00.770
I am sorry that yourleisure serves you not.

2533
02:13:03.170 --> 02:13:09.570
Antonio, gratify thisgentleman,

2534
02:13:09.570 --> 02:13:14.570
for in my mind, you aremuch bound to him.

2535
02:13:20.270 --> 02:13:24.870
Most worthy gentleman, Iand my friend have, byyour wisdom,

2536
02:13:24.870 --> 02:13:27.500
been this day acquitted ofgrievous penalties.

2537
02:13:27.500 --> 02:13:30.970
in lieu whereof 3,000ducats, due unto the Jew,

2538
02:13:30.970 --> 02:13:33.600
we freely cope yourcourteous pains withal.

2539
02:13:33.600 --> 02:13:35.700
And stand indebted, overand above,

2540
02:13:35.700 --> 02:13:38.330
in love and service to youevermore.

2541
02:13:38.330 --> 02:13:40.530
He is well paid that iswell satisfied.

2542
02:13:40.530 --> 02:13:43.230
And I, delivering you, amsatisfied

2543
02:13:43.230 --> 02:13:45.030
and therein do accountmyself well paid.

2544
02:13:45.030 --> 02:13:46.870
My mind was never yet moremercenary.

2545
02:13:46.870 --> 02:13:49.930
I pray you know me when wemeet again.

2546
02:13:49.930 --> 02:13:51.600
I wish you well, so I takemy leave.

2547
02:13:51.600 --> 02:13:54.670
Dear sir, of force I mustattempt you further.

2548
02:13:54.670 --> 02:13:58.230
Take some remembrance of usas a tribute, not as fee.

2549
02:13:58.230 --> 02:14:00.100
Grant me two things, Ipray:

2550
02:14:00.100 --> 02:14:02.800
not to deny me, and topardon me.

2551
02:14:02.800 --> 02:14:06.700
You press me far, andtherefore I will yield.

2552
02:14:06.700 --> 02:14:07.970
Give me your gloves.

2553
02:14:07.970 --> 02:14:09.970
I'll wear them for yoursake.

2554
02:14:09.970 --> 02:14:13.800
And for your love, I'lltake this ring from you.

2555
02:14:13.800 --> 02:14:15.230
Do not draw back yourhand.

2556
02:14:15.230 --> 02:14:18.100
I'll take no more, and you,in love, cannot deny me this.

2557
02:14:18.100 --> 02:14:20.370
This ring, good sir?

2558
02:14:20.370 --> 02:14:21.870
Alack, it is a trifle.

2559
02:14:21.870 --> 02:14:23.730
I will not shame myself togive you this.

2560
02:14:23.730 --> 02:14:25.430
I will have nothing elsebut only this.

2561
02:14:25.430 --> 02:14:27.130
And now methinks I have amind to it.

2562
02:14:27.130 --> 02:14:29.330
There's more depends onthis than on the value.

2563
02:14:29.330 --> 02:14:32.500
The dearest ring in Venicewill I give you

2564
02:14:32.500 --> 02:14:34.230
and find it out byproclamation.

2565
02:14:34.230 --> 02:14:36.870
Only for this, I pray youpardon me.

2566
02:14:36.870 --> 02:14:38.530
I see, sir, you areliberal in offers.

2567
02:14:38.530 --> 02:14:41.400
You taught me first to beg,and now methinks you teach me

2568
02:14:41.400 --> 02:14:42.830
how a beggar should beanswered.

2569
02:14:42.830 --> 02:14:46.170
This ring, good sir, wasgiven me by my wife.

2570
02:14:46.170 --> 02:14:48.600
And when she put it on,she made me vow

2571
02:14:48.600 --> 02:14:52.630
I should neither sell norlose nor give it.

2572
02:14:52.630 --> 02:14:55.670
That 'scuse serves manymen to save their gifts,

2573
02:14:55.670 --> 02:14:57.500
and if your wife be not amadwoman

2574
02:14:57.500 --> 02:14:59.770
and know how well I havedeserved this ring,

2575
02:14:59.770 --> 02:15:03.930
she would not hold outenemy forever for givingit to me.

2576
02:15:03.930 --> 02:15:05.930
Well, peace be with you.

2577
02:15:07.700 --> 02:15:10.700
My lord, Bassanio, let himhave the ring.

2578
02:15:10.700 --> 02:15:12.470
Let his deserving, and mylove withal

2579
02:15:12.470 --> 02:15:15.030
be valued 'gainst yourwife's commandment.

2580
02:15:34.570 --> 02:15:37.770
Go, Gratiano, run andovertake him.

2581
02:15:37.770 --> 02:15:39.070
Give him the ring.

2582
02:15:39.070 --> 02:15:41.170
Bring him, if thou canst,unto Antonio's house.

2583
02:15:41.170 --> 02:15:43.900
Away, make haste.

2584
02:15:45.730 --> 02:15:49.200
Come, you and I willthither presently,

2585
02:15:49.200 --> 02:15:52.500
and in the morning early, wewill both fly toward Belmont.

2586
02:15:52.500 --> 02:15:55.930
Come, Antonio.

2587
02:16:07.000 --> 02:16:08.300
Inquire the Jew's houseout.

2588
02:16:08.300 --> 02:16:10.400
Give him this deed; lethim sign it.

2589
02:16:10.400 --> 02:16:13.070
We'll away tonight and be aday before our husbands home.

2590
02:16:13.070 --> 02:16:15.330
This deed will be wellwelcome to Lorenzo.

2591
02:16:15.330 --> 02:16:16.400
Fair sir!

2592
02:16:17.830 --> 02:16:19.900
You are well o'erta'en.

2593
02:16:19.900 --> 02:16:22.570
My lord, Bassanio, uponmore advice,

2594
02:16:22.570 --> 02:16:24.530
hath sent you here thisring

2595
02:16:24.530 --> 02:16:26.700
and doth entreat yourcompany at dinner.

2596
02:16:26.700 --> 02:16:28.630
That cannot be.

2597
02:16:28.630 --> 02:16:32.970
His ring I do accept mostthankfully, and so I prayyou tell him.

2598
02:16:32.970 --> 02:16:35.670
Furthermore, I pray youshow my youth oldShylock's house.

2599
02:16:35.670 --> 02:16:37.170
That will I do.

2600
02:16:37.170 --> 02:16:40.470
Sir, I would speak withyou.

2601
02:16:40.470 --> 02:16:43.270
I'll see if I can get myhusband's ring,

2602
02:16:43.270 --> 02:16:45.470
which I did make him swearto keep forever.

2603
02:16:45.470 --> 02:16:46.870
Thou mayst, I warrant.

2604
02:16:46.870 --> 02:16:49.200
We shall have old swearing

2605
02:16:49.200 --> 02:16:51.230
that they did give therings away to men.

2606
02:16:51.230 --> 02:16:53.230
But we'll outface them andoutswear them too.

2607
02:16:53.230 --> 02:16:55.230
Away, make haste.

2608
02:16:55.230 --> 02:16:58.270
Thou know'st where I willtarry.

2609
02:16:58.270 --> 02:17:00.770
Come, good sir, will youshow me to this house?

2610
02:17:08.630 --> 02:17:10.530
The moon shines bright.

2611
02:17:18.170 --> 02:17:19.700
In such a night as this,

2612
02:17:19.700 --> 02:17:24.100
when the sweet wind didgently kiss the trees

2613
02:17:24.100 --> 02:17:25.730
and they did make nonoise,

2614
02:17:25.730 --> 02:17:27.670
in such a night,

2615
02:17:27.670 --> 02:17:30.470
Troilus methinks mountedthe Trojan walls

2616
02:17:30.470 --> 02:17:33.600
and sighed his soultowards the Grecian tents

2617
02:17:33.600 --> 02:17:35.470
where Cressid lay thatnight.

2618
02:17:35.470 --> 02:17:42.970
In such a night did Thisbefearfully o'ertrip the dew

2619
02:17:42.970 --> 02:17:46.400
and saw the lion's shadowere himself

2620
02:17:46.400 --> 02:17:49.400
and ran dismayed away.

2621
02:17:49.400 --> 02:17:54.100
In such a night stood Didowith a willow in her hand

2622
02:17:54.100 --> 02:17:55.770
upon the wild sea-banks

2623
02:17:55.770 --> 02:17:59.330
and waft her love to comeagain to Carthage.

2624
02:17:59.330 --> 02:18:03.730
In such a night, Medeagathered

2625
02:18:03.730 --> 02:18:10.930
the enchanted herbs thatdid renew old Aeson.

2626
02:18:10.930 --> 02:18:16.030
In such a night didJessica steal from thewealthy Jew,

2627
02:18:16.030 --> 02:18:18.600
and with an unthrift love,

2628
02:18:18.600 --> 02:18:22.000
did run from Venice as faras Belmont.

2629
02:18:22.000 --> 02:18:23.800
In such a night

2630
02:18:23.800 --> 02:18:26.670
did young Lorenzo swear heloved her well,

2631
02:18:26.670 --> 02:18:29.870
stealing her soul withmany vows of faith

2632
02:18:29.870 --> 02:18:32.300
and ne'er a true one.

2633
02:18:32.300 --> 02:18:38.170
In such a night did prettyJessica, like a little shrew,

2634
02:18:38.170 --> 02:18:44.070
slander her love, and heforgave it her.

2635
02:18:44.070 --> 02:18:46.870
I would out-night you, didnobody come.

2636
02:18:46.870 --> 02:18:49.930
But hark, I hear thefooting of a man.

2637
02:18:49.930 --> 02:18:51.800
Who comes so fast insilence of the night?

2638
02:18:51.800 --> 02:18:53.070
A friend.

2639
02:18:53.070 --> 02:18:54.270
A friend?

2640
02:18:54.270 --> 02:18:55.470
What friend?

2641
02:18:55.470 --> 02:18:57.430
Your name, I pray you,friend.

2642
02:18:57.430 --> 02:18:58.870
Stephano is my name,

2643
02:18:58.870 --> 02:19:00.870
and I bring word that mymistress will,

2644
02:19:00.870 --> 02:19:03.230
before the break of day,be here at Belmont.

2645
02:19:03.230 --> 02:19:05.470
She doth stray about byholy crosses

2646
02:19:05.470 --> 02:19:07.600
where she kneels and praysfor happy wedlock hours.

2647
02:19:07.600 --> 02:19:09.030
Who comes with her?

2648
02:19:09.030 --> 02:19:11.200
None but a holy hermit andher maid.

2649
02:19:11.200 --> 02:19:13.300
I pray you, is my masteryet returned?

2650
02:19:13.300 --> 02:19:15.500
He is not yet, nor we havenot heard from him.

2651
02:19:15.500 --> 02:19:17.670
But go we in.

2652
02:19:17.670 --> 02:19:19.300
I pray thee, Jessica,

2653
02:19:19.300 --> 02:19:22.870
and ceremoniously let usprepare

2654
02:19:22.870 --> 02:19:24.870
some welcome for themistress of the house.

2655
02:19:24.870 --> 02:19:26.500
Sola, sola!

2656
02:19:26.500 --> 02:19:27.700
Wo ha, hoo.

2657
02:19:27.700 --> 02:19:28.900
Sola! Sola!

2658
02:19:28.900 --> 02:19:30.070
Who calls?

2659
02:19:30.070 --> 02:19:31.170
Sola!

2660
02:19:31.170 --> 02:19:32.730
Did you see masterLorenzo?

2661
02:19:32.730 --> 02:19:34.600
Master Lorenzo-oo?

2662
02:19:34.600 --> 02:19:35.800
Sola! Sola!

2663
02:19:35.800 --> 02:19:36.970
Leave holloaing, man,here.

2664
02:19:36.970 --> 02:19:38.070
Sola!

2665
02:19:38.070 --> 02:19:39.230
Where?

2666
02:19:39.230 --> 02:19:40.330
Here!

2667
02:19:40.330 --> 02:19:42.970
Tell him there's a postcome from my master

2668
02:19:42.970 --> 02:19:45.530
with his horn full of goodnews.

2669
02:19:45.530 --> 02:19:48.330
My master will be here eremorning.

2670
02:19:55.930 --> 02:19:59.100
Sweet soul, let's in andthere expect their coming.

2671
02:19:59.100 --> 02:20:01.270
And yet no matter.

2672
02:20:01.270 --> 02:20:03.130
Why should we go in?

2673
02:20:03.130 --> 02:20:05.070
My friend, Stephano,signify, I pray you,

2674
02:20:05.070 --> 02:20:06.230
within the house--

2675
02:20:06.230 --> 02:20:07.530
your mistress is at hand--

2676
02:20:07.530 --> 02:20:11.600
and bring your music forthinto the air.

2677
02:20:15.930 --> 02:20:19.500
How sweet the moonlightsleeps upon this bank.

2678
02:20:19.500 --> 02:20:20.770
Here will we sit

2679
02:20:20.770 --> 02:20:26.170
and let the sounds ofmusic creep in our ears.

2680
02:20:26.170 --> 02:20:29.630
Soft stillness and thenight become the touchesof sweet harmony.

2681
02:20:29.630 --> 02:20:31.870
Sit, Jessica.

2682
02:20:39.500 --> 02:20:41.670
Look how the floor ofheaven

2683
02:20:41.670 --> 02:20:44.800
is thick inlaid withpatens of bright gold.

2684
02:20:47.330 --> 02:20:49.730
There's not the smallestorb which thou behold'st

2685
02:20:49.730 --> 02:20:52.630
but in his motion like anangel sings

2686
02:20:52.630 --> 02:20:57.430
still quiring to theyoung-eyed cherubins.

2687
02:20:57.430 --> 02:21:01.130
Such harmony is inimmortal souls.

2688
02:21:01.130 --> 02:21:04.230
But whilst this muddyvesture of decay

2689
02:21:04.230 --> 02:21:09.100
doth grossly close it in,we cannot hear it.

2690
02:21:12.600 --> 02:21:15.770
Come, ho, and wake Dianawith a hymn.

2691
02:21:15.770 --> 02:21:19.730
With sweetest touches,pierce your mistress' ear

2692
02:21:19.730 --> 02:21:22.270
and draw her home withmusic.

2693
02:21:30.730 --> 02:21:34.100
I am never merry when Ihear sweet music.

2694
02:21:36.100 --> 02:21:39.670
The reason is your spiritsare attentive.

2695
02:21:39.670 --> 02:21:44.330
For do but note a wild andwanton herd

2696
02:21:44.330 --> 02:21:46.930
or race of youthful andunhandled colts

2697
02:21:46.930 --> 02:21:50.370
fetching mad bounds,bellowing and neighing loud,

2698
02:21:50.370 --> 02:21:53.670
which is the hot conditionof their blood.

2699
02:21:53.670 --> 02:21:56.330
If they but hear perchancea trumpet sound

2700
02:21:56.330 --> 02:21:59.630
or any air of music touchtheir ears,

2701
02:21:59.630 --> 02:22:02.030
you shall perceive themmake a mutual stand,

2702
02:22:02.030 --> 02:22:05.700
their savage eyes turnedto a modest gaze

2703
02:22:05.700 --> 02:22:08.500
by the sweet power ofmusic.

2704
02:22:08.500 --> 02:22:10.830
Therefore the poet didfeign

2705
02:22:10.830 --> 02:22:13.570
that Orpheus drew trees,stones, and floods,

2706
02:22:13.570 --> 02:22:16.930
since naught so stockish,hard, and full of rage,

2707
02:22:16.930 --> 02:22:20.700
but music for the timedoth change his nature.

2708
02:22:24.200 --> 02:22:26.570
The man that hath no musicin himself,

2709
02:22:26.570 --> 02:22:30.800
nor is not moved withconcord of sweet sounds,

2710
02:22:30.800 --> 02:22:34.000
is fit for treasons,stratagems, and spoils.

2711
02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:37.100
The motions of his spiritare dull as night,

2712
02:22:37.100 --> 02:22:40.800
and his affections dark asErebus.

2713
02:22:40.800 --> 02:22:44.230
Let no such man betrusted.

2714
02:22:48.670 --> 02:22:50.370
Mark the music.

2715
02:23:23.830 --> 02:23:25.830
That light we see isburning in my hall.

2716
02:23:25.830 --> 02:23:30.430
How far that little candlethrows his beams.

2717
02:23:30.430 --> 02:23:34.530
So shines a good deed in anaughty world.

2718
02:23:34.530 --> 02:23:37.100
When the moon shone, wedid not see the candle.

2719
02:23:37.100 --> 02:23:40.530
So doth the greater glorydim the less.

2720
02:23:40.530 --> 02:23:43.270
A substitute shinesbrightly as a king

2721
02:23:43.270 --> 02:23:44.500
until a king be by,

2722
02:23:44.500 --> 02:23:46.900
and then his state emptiesitself

2723
02:23:46.900 --> 02:23:49.170
as doth an inland brookinto the main of waters.

2724
02:23:49.170 --> 02:23:52.430
Music, hark.

2725
02:23:52.430 --> 02:23:55.470
It is your music, madam,of the house.

2726
02:23:55.470 --> 02:23:59.030
Nothing is good, I see,without respect.

2727
02:23:59.030 --> 02:24:01.170
Methinks it sounds muchsweeter than by day.

2728
02:24:01.170 --> 02:24:04.730
Silence bestows thatvirtue on it, madam.

2729
02:24:04.730 --> 02:24:06.370
The crow doth sing assweetly as the lark

2730
02:24:06.370 --> 02:24:07.770
when neither is attended,

2731
02:24:07.770 --> 02:24:11.200
and I think thenightingale, if she shouldsing by day

2732
02:24:11.200 --> 02:24:12.500
when every goose iscackling,

2733
02:24:12.500 --> 02:24:16.130
would be thought no bettera musician than the wren.

2734
02:24:16.130 --> 02:24:19.400
How many things by seasonseasoned

2735
02:24:19.400 --> 02:24:22.130
are to their right praiseand true perfection.

2736
02:24:22.130 --> 02:24:26.070
Peace, ho.

2737
02:24:26.070 --> 02:24:29.400
The moon sleeps with Endymionand would not be awaked.

2738
02:24:29.400 --> 02:24:34.430
That is the voice, or I ammuch deceived, of Portia.

2739
02:24:34.430 --> 02:24:36.670
He knows me as the blindman knows the cuckoo

2740
02:24:36.670 --> 02:24:37.970
by the bad voice.

2741
02:24:40.730 --> 02:24:42.630
Dear lady, welcome home.

2742
02:24:42.630 --> 02:24:45.170
We have been praying forour husbands' welfare,

2743
02:24:45.170 --> 02:24:48.070
which speed, we hope, thebetter for our words.

2744
02:24:48.070 --> 02:24:49.670
Are they returned?

2745
02:24:49.670 --> 02:24:51.170
Madam, they are not yet,

2746
02:24:51.170 --> 02:24:53.130
but there has come amessenger before

2747
02:24:53.130 --> 02:24:54.500
to signify their coming.

2748
02:24:54.500 --> 02:24:56.770
Go in, Nerissa, give orderto my servants

2749
02:24:56.770 --> 02:24:59.100
that they take no note at allof our being absent hence.

2750
02:24:59.100 --> 02:25:01.800
Nor you, Lorenzo--Jessica, nor you.

2751
02:25:01.800 --> 02:25:03.430
Your husband is at hand.

2752
02:25:03.430 --> 02:25:04.600
I hear his trumpet.

2753
02:25:04.600 --> 02:25:06.770
We are no telltales,madam.

2754
02:25:06.770 --> 02:25:08.070
Fear you not.

2755
02:25:08.070 --> 02:25:10.570
This night methinks is butthe daylight sick.

2756
02:25:10.570 --> 02:25:11.900
It looks a little paler.

2757
02:25:11.900 --> 02:25:16.100
'Tis a day such as the dayis when the sun is hid.

2758
02:25:16.100 --> 02:25:18.170
We should hold day withthe antipodes

2759
02:25:18.170 --> 02:25:20.570
if you would walk inabsence of the sun.

2760
02:25:20.570 --> 02:25:23.070
Let me give light, but letme not be light,

2761
02:25:23.070 --> 02:25:25.400
for a light wife doth makea heavy husband,

2762
02:25:25.400 --> 02:25:27.470
and never be Bassanio sofor me.

2763
02:25:27.470 --> 02:25:29.470
But God sort all.

2764
02:25:29.470 --> 02:25:31.600
You are welcome home, mylord.

2765
02:25:31.600 --> 02:25:33.570
I thank you, madam.

2766
02:25:38.070 --> 02:25:39.870
Give welcome to my friend.

2767
02:25:39.870 --> 02:25:41.700
This is the man.

2768
02:25:41.700 --> 02:25:43.670
This is Antonio,

2769
02:25:43.670 --> 02:25:45.800
to whom I am so infinitelybound.

2770
02:25:45.800 --> 02:25:47.830
You should in all sense bemuch bound to him,

2771
02:25:47.830 --> 02:25:50.670
for, as I hear, he wasmuch bound for you.

2772
02:25:50.670 --> 02:25:52.600
No more than I am wellacquitted of.

2773
02:25:52.600 --> 02:25:54.830
Sir, you are very welcometo our house.

2774
02:25:54.830 --> 02:25:56.800
It must appear in otherways than words.

2775
02:25:56.800 --> 02:25:59.230
Therefore I scant thisbreathing courtesy.

2776
02:25:59.230 --> 02:26:02.130
By yonder moon, I swearyou do me wrong.

2777
02:26:02.130 --> 02:26:04.400
In faith, I gave it to thejudge's clerk.

2778
02:26:04.400 --> 02:26:06.530
Would he were gelt thathad it for my part

2779
02:26:06.530 --> 02:26:08.270
since you do take it,love, so much at heart.

2780
02:26:08.270 --> 02:26:09.370
A quarrel?

2781
02:26:09.370 --> 02:26:10.530
Ho, already?

2782
02:26:10.530 --> 02:26:11.730
What's the matter?

2783
02:26:11.730 --> 02:26:14.100
About a hoop of gold, a paltryring that she did give me

2784
02:26:14.100 --> 02:26:17.570
whose posy was, for allthe world, like cutler'spoetry upon a knife.

2785
02:26:17.570 --> 02:26:19.900
"Love me, and leave menot."

2786
02:26:19.900 --> 02:26:22.230
What talk you of the posyor the value?

2787
02:26:22.230 --> 02:26:24.770
You swore to me when I didgive it to you

2788
02:26:24.770 --> 02:26:26.870
that you would wear ittill your hour of death

2789
02:26:26.870 --> 02:26:29.970
and that it should liewith you in your grave.

2790
02:26:29.970 --> 02:26:32.930
